    <section>
        <h2>Lesson 1: CSS Fundamentals</h2>
        <p>
            CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) controls the appearance of web pages. It separates content (HTML) from presentation (colors, fonts, layouts).
        </p>
        <h3>Code Snippet: Basic Styling</h3>
        <pre><code>
body {
  background: #f0f4f8;
  color: #222;
  font-family: 'Segoe UI', Arial, sans-serif;
}

h1 {
  color: #0a84ff;
  text-align: center;
}

p {
  font-size: 1.2em;
  line-height: 1.7;
  padding: 10px 0;
}
        </code></pre>
        <h4>Detailed Step-by-Step Explanation</h4>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>body:</strong> Sets the general background, font, and text color for the whole page.</li>
            <li><strong>h1:</strong> Changes the color of all main headings and centers them.</li>
            <li><strong>p:</strong> Increases the font size, improves readability, and adds vertical padding.</li>
        </ol>
        <h4>Exercise</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Change the background color to your favorite color.</li>
            <li>Make all paragraphs italic.</li>
            <li>Center all images on the page using a CSS selector.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Lesson 2: Flexbox Layout</h2>
        <p>Flexbox is a powerful layout model that allows you to create flexible and responsive layouts.</p>
        <h3>Code Snippet: Flexbox Grid</h3>
        <pre><code>
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 16px;
  justify-content: center;
}

.card {
  background: #fff;
  border-radius: 8px;
  box-shadow: 0 1px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.10);
  padding: 24px;
  flex: 1 1 300px;
  max-width: 350px;
}
        </code></pre>
        <h4>Explanation</h4>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>display: flex;</strong> turns <code>.container</code> into a flex container.</li>
            <li><strong>flex-wrap: wrap;</strong> makes the items wrap to the next line when needed.</li>
            <li><strong>gap:</strong> adds space between child elements.</li>
            <li><strong>.card:</strong> sets the card appearance, size, and makes it responsive.</li>
        </ol>
        <h4>Exercise</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Create a flex container with three cards. Make the cards stack vertically on small screens using a media query.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Lesson 3: Responsive Design with Media Queries</h2>
        <h3>Code Snippet: Media Query</h3>
        <pre><code>
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .container {
    flex-direction: column;
    padding: 10px;
  }
  h1 {
    color: #d7263d;
  }
}
        </code></pre>
        <h4>Explanation</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>When the screen is 600px or less, <code>.container</code> stacks its items vertically and adds padding.</li>
            <li>The <code>h1</code> color changes for smaller screens, making your site adaptable for mobile devices.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Exercise</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Add a media query to make all text centered on screens smaller than 500px.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Tips, Tricks & Resources</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Use <a href="https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/a-guide-to-flexbox/" target="_blank">CSS Tricks Flexbox Guide</a> for quick layout solutions.</li>
            <li>Try <a href="https://flexboxfroggy.com/" target="_blank">Flexbox Froggy</a> for hands-on Flexbox practice.</li>
            <li>Utilize CSS variables for theming:</li>
        </ul>
        <pre><code>
:root {
  --primary: #0a84ff;
}

h1 {
  color: var(--primary);
}
        </code></pre>
        <ul>
            <li>Use browser DevTools to live-edit your CSS and experiment quickly.</li>
        </ul>
